                                <p><hi rend="initialcap">C</hi>ASE 191.—<name type="person" key="719">Private Martin Riley</name>,
                                                <name type="organization" key="700">Co. C, 122d
                                                Pa.</name>; admitted <date type="admit" when="1863-04-21">April 21, 1863</date>.  Continued
                                        fever.  Died <date type="death" when="1863-05-24">May
                                                24</date>.  <hi rend="italic">Post-mortem</hi>
                                        examination <date type="autopsy" when="1863-05-25">twenty hours after death</date>: The body was much
                                        emaciated. The lungs were healthy, but the bronchial tubes
                                        contained a purulent secretion. The heart was softened and
                                        pale; a small point of pus was found at its apex; the mitral
                                        valve was thickened and slightly roughened. The stomach was
                                        nearly filled with bile. The liver was healthy; the
                                        gall-bladder nearly empty. The duodenum and jejunum were
                                        normal; the ileum inflamed and Peyer's patches ulcerated;
                                        the ascending colon congested in spots, the transverse and
                                        descending portions healthy. The kidneys were normal.—<hi rend="italic"><name type="person" key="181">Act. Ass't. Surg. A. H.
                                                  Haven</name>, <name type="hospital" key="173">Harewood Hospital</name>, Washington, D. C.</hi></p>                        
